<head type="main-authorial" rend="center">2d day</head>
<dateline><date when="1865-05-24">May 24, 1865</date></dateline>

<milestone unit="undeclared" rend="horbar-short-left"/>

<ab>15th &amp; 17th Corps</ab>
<ab><add place="interlinear" rend="unmarked">First the broad capacious open waiting avenue—then singly</add> Gen Sherman, passing rapidly by—the sudden shouts, quite tumultous,—but he pays no more attention to it, than if <del rend="overstrike">he</del> it was the wind blowing—</ab> 

<ab>—the large <add place="supralinear" rend="insertion"><del rend="overstrike">&amp;</del> magnificent</add>  bouquet—he turns, one of his generals <add place="interlinear" rend="unmarked">from behind</add> rides up &amp; takes it from him—<del rend="overstrike">a</del> &amp; still the shouting crowd, &amp; still the perfect deafness &amp;

<pb xml:id="leaf011v" facs="uva.00062.017.jpg" type="verso"/>

<pb xml:id="leaf012r" facs="uva.00062.018.jpg" type="recto"/>

immobility of the great soldier—with <subst><del rend="overwrite" seq="1">a</del> <add place="over" rend="overwrite" seq="2">I</add></subst> think a shade of <add place="supralinear" rend="unmarked">scornfulness &amp;</add> haught<subst><del rend="overwrite" seq="1">y</del><add rend="overwrite" place="over" seq="2">i</add></subst><del rend="overstrike">ness</del> <del rend="overstrike">&amp; scornful p</del> passion on his nervous face. (Haughty here to this ephemeral popular hurrahing, but, as I know from many a soldier of his army, <del rend="overstrike">res</del></ab>
</div1>

